<DOC><DOCNO> AP891001-0070 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-10-01-89 2132EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r a AM-Governors'Conference     10-01 0281</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Governors' Conference,0289</SECOND><HEAD>Midwest Governors Open Conference to Discuss Agriculture, Trade</HEAD><BYLINE>By JOYA L. WESLEY</BYLINE><BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE><DATELINE>MILWAUKEE (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The Midwest is shaking its ``rust belt'' imageand should be promoted as a region with hard workers, a healthyeconomy and less crime, participants in the Midwestern Governors'Conference said Sunday.   ``What we're trying to do is promote this region,'' WisconsinGov. Tommy G. Thompson said as governors and other representativesof 13 states gathered for the start of the 27th annual conference,which continues through Tuesday.   Thompson, the conference host, said news media have dismissedthe Midwest as part of the ``rust belt,'' referring to the loss oftraditional manufacturing jobs when industries leave a region. Buthe said the Midwest has begun to shake that image.   Gov. Terry E. Branstad of Iowa agreed, citing a recent articlein Newsweek magazine.   ``The heartland is hot,'' he said. ``I think this region is in avery enviable position.''   Branstad said the area must market its strong work ethic,healthy economy, educational programs, low cost of living andrelatively low crime rate.   Speakers scheduled to appear at the conference include U.S.Agriculture Secretary Clayton Yeutter and Deputy Secretary of StateLawrence Eagleburger.   During business sessions of the conference, Thompson said thegovernors would work to develop cooperative efforts to fightillegal drugs and to protect the environment.   Also, governors of the five states of the northern MississippiRiver will sign a Mississippi Pact to protect the river, whichThompson called an environmental and economic resource.   The states in the Midwestern Governors' Association areWisconsin, Missouri, Minnesota, Iowa, Illinois, North Dakota, SouthDakota, Kansas, Michigan, Ohio, Indiana, Kentucky and Nebraska.</TEXT></DOC>